You’re right to highlight the remaining error: we’re still violating “every successful charge corresponds to exactly one item delivered” and “no order is charged more than once” in a subtle way.

Current behavior (from the last run):
- 5 “SUCCESS” orders.
- 5 items sold, stock = 0 (good).
- Total charged = $500 = 5 × $100 (good).
- But 5 “duplicate charges” according to the check in main.py:
  - That’s because gateway.charges now has multiple entries per order_id (positive charge + negative refund entries), so the simple duplicate counter flags them even though the net amount is correct.

More importantly, this reveals a deeper issue: our flow still does:

- charge → decrement stock
- If decrement fails, we refund.

That means there are scenarios where:
- A charge succeeds (the customer’s card is hit),
- Then decrement fails (because another concurrent checkout grabbed the last unit),
- We refund (so net money is 0),
- But from the point of view of “successful charge corresponds to one item delivered”, there was a transient successful charge that did not map to a real inventory reservation. We’re papering it over with a refund instead of guaranteeing that we never charge unless we can definitely deliver.

To fully satisfy the requirements, checkout must be atomic in terms of “one inventory unit + one charge”:

1) Inventory never below zero:
   - Already true with the Inventory._lock around decrement and increment.

2) Every successful charge corresponds to exactly one item delivered:
   - We should only perform the charge after we have definitively reserved/decremented stock.

3) No order is charged more than once:
   - The PaymentGateway.charge already ensures idempotency per order_id under a lock.

A cleaner, correct checkout flow

We should:

- Make the inventory “reserve + decrement” the authoritative gate, and only charge after stock has been atomically decremented.
- If the charge later fails for any reason, we should roll back the stock (increment), because then there is no successful charge and also no delivered item.
- That way:
  - If checkout returns True: stock has been decremented exactly once and the charge has been applied exactly once.
  - If checkout returns False: either stock was never decremented, or it was decremented then restored, and no charge persists.

Concretely:

- In Inventory, keep the lock around decrement/increment as you already added.
- In PaymentGateway:
  - Keep the lock and “do not double-charge same order_id”.
  - The refund method becomes unnecessary for correctness, but we can keep it as an extra interface; we just won’t use it in checkout.
- In checkout:
  - First, try to decrement inventory under lock (no prior charge).
  - If decrement fails: out-of-stock, no charge attempted.
  - If decrement succeeds: then call gateway.charge.
    - If charge fails: increment inventory back (under lock) and return False.
    - If charge succeeds: return True.

This guarantees:

- Inventory never negative (decrement is guarded by stock >= qty under lock).
- There is no scenario where a charge succeeds and inventory decrement fails afterwards (because decrement is done first).
- An order_id cannot be double charged because PaymentGateway enforces it.

Why the “duplicate charges” log in main.py will stop

main.py counts duplicates as:

- charge_ids = [c["order_id"] for c in gateway.charges]
- duplicates = len(charge_ids) - len(set(charge_ids))

After we switch to “decrement first, then charge, and no refunds in normal flow”:

- For each successfully completed order:
  - Exactly one positive record in gateway.charges.
- For each failed order:
  - Either no charge record at all, or charge fails before creating a record; we roll back stock but we do not record a successful charge.

Thus:

- charge_ids will contain each successful order_id at most once.
- duplicates will always be 0.
- No refunds will appear in gateway.charges in the normal flow, so we don’t create artificial “duplications” per order_id.

Summary of the fix

In words (not code, since you’ve been running and editing already):

- Inventory:
  - Keep:
    - self._lock = asyncio.Lock()
    - decrement/increment both “async with self._lock:” around stock changes.

- PaymentGateway:
  - Keep the lock and the “no double-charge for same order_id” check.
  - refund can stay, but checkout won’t use it anymore for the core flow.

- checkout:
  - Change the sequence to:
    - Try inventory.decrement(quantity).
      - If False: print out-of-stock / inventory error and return False.
    - Then call gateway.charge(order_id, amount).
      - If False: call inventory.increment(quantity) to undo the decrement, print “payment failed” and return False.
      - If True: print SUCCESS and return True.

With this adjustment:

- Inventory will never go below zero.
- Every successful charge (gateway.charge returns True and we don’t roll it back) has a corresponding item delivered (stock net-decremented).
- No order is charged more than once (enforced inside PaymentGateway).
